# Chezmoi Managed Home

## Core Rule

- Never edit rendered home paths directly when a chezmoi source exists.
- Edit the active chezmoi source repo and apply it. Current source: `{{ .chezmoi.sourceDir }}`.
- If the target is not managed by chezmoi, prefer adding it to chezmoi instead of making an unmanaged home edit.
- Use `chezmoi managed <path>` or inspect the repo source mapping when unsure.
- `chezmoi apply` renders source to target. Target edits vanish on the next apply.

## Common Sources

| Target                              | Source                                          |
| ----------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------- |
| `~/.config/git/hooks/post-checkout` | `dot_config/git/hooks/executable_post-checkout` |
| `~/.gitconfig`                      | `dot_gitconfig.tmpl`                            |
| `~/.zshrc`                          | `dot_zshrc.tmpl`                                |
| `~/airules`                         | `exact_airules`                                 |
| `run_*` scripts                     | `.chezmoiscripts/{posix,macos,linux,windows}/`  |

## Conventions

- `dot_foo` -> `~/.foo`
- `dot_config/` -> `~/.config/`
- `.tmpl` -> Go template
- `executable_` -> executable target
- `run_once_` / `run_after_` -> run by `chezmoi apply`
- Use `.tmpl` only when the rendered file needs host-specific values or secrets. Prefer app env vars plus env templates when the app can expand `${VAR}`.

## Verify Edits

- Run `timeout 2 chezmoi diff` when practical.
- Run `timeout 2 chezmoi apply -v` when practical.
- If `timeout` fires, chezmoi is waiting for input; tell user to run `czapply` manually.

## Agent Behavior

- Keep legacy code cleanup leftovers short. Assume one user/app state; if one cleanup was done once, that is enough. Mention repeat cleanup as a consideration in the summary and ask before adding it.
- Before finishing tasks that run commands, check `git status --short` for unexpected generated files or edits.
- Before finishing tasks that spawn background processes, check `pty_list` and kill task-owned sessions.
- Remove task-owned temporary files, logs, caches, build outputs, and generated artifacts unless they are intended results.
- Do not remove unrelated user files or changes.

## Packages

- Managed package files: `install/*file` (`npmfile`, `Brewfile`, `Wingetfile`, `uv-file`, `Gofile`, etc.).
- Managed package files are authoritative; `make mise-packages` should remove leftover globals not present in the corresponding list.
- Avoid duplicate package ownership across managed package files. A tool must be managed by one source of truth only: prefer cross-platform tool/language managers when they work across targets; use OS package files only for OS-specific apps, system libraries, GUI apps, drivers, fonts, or tools unavailable/unsuitable through the cross-platform manager. If moving a package between managers, remove it from the old manager file and uninstall/prune it from the current machine.
- When removing entries from managed package files, also run the matching uninstall/prune command for the current machine.
- Package docs do not override dotfile package management. If docs say `npm install -g`, `brew install`, `winget install`, `uv tool install`, `go install`, etc., first add the package to the matching managed package file. Avoid one-off installs unless the user explicitly asks.
- For winget packages, add the package ID to `install/Wingetfile` first, then run `make winget-packages`; do not hand-run `winget install` unless the repo target is unavailable or debugging it.
- If hand-running `winget install` is necessary, use `--silent --disable-interactivity --accept-package-agreements --accept-source-agreements`.

## Cross-Platform

- Keep Arch/MacOS/Win11 same where possible.
- Windows: use `pwsh.exe` (PS 7), never `powershell.exe` (PS 5).
- Windows MinGW: install WinLibs with `winget install --id BrechtSanders.WinLibs.POSIX.UCRT --exact --silent --disable-interactivity --accept-package-agreements --accept-source-agreements`; do not use MSYS2 `pacman` for MinGW.
- Check both `.chezmoitemplates/env_vars_ps1` and `env_vars_posix`. Same for aliases and env-backed app config.
- Do not hand-code simple aliases in shell templates. Add them to `.chezmoidata.toml` `[sharedAliases]` and let templates render them.

## Scripts

- Python is available on every target system; prefer it for nontrivial cross-platform alias utilities when compilation is not desired.
